              <h2>How Arkansas income tax is calculated</h2>
              <p>
                Arkansas has a progressive state income tax with multiple
                brackets. Your income is divided into ranges, and each range is
                taxed at its own rate. This calculator approximates your
                Arkansas liability using current brackets and standard
                deductions.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Conceptual formula</strong><br />
                <code>
                  Arkansas tax = (Tax on first bracket) + (Tax on second
                  bracket) + ... − Credits
                </code>
              </div>

              <h3>1. Determine your Arkansas taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                Start from your federal adjusted gross income (AGI), then apply
                Arkansas‑specific additions and subtractions to arrive at
                Arkansas taxable income. This tool assumes you already have an
                estimate of that number.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Arkansas taxable income</strong> ≈ Wages + other
                  income − pre‑tax deductions − adjustments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Some types of income (for example, Social Security benefits)
                  may be exempt in Arkansas.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Apply the Arkansas standard or itemized deduction</h3>
              <p>
                Arkansas allows you to claim either the standard deduction or
                your Arkansas itemized deductions, whichever is larger. In this
                calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If you leave itemized deductions at $0, we apply an estimated
                  standard deduction based on filing status.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you enter a positive amount for itemized deductions, we use
                  that instead of the standard deduction.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Apply Arkansas tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                After deductions, your remaining income is taxed using
                Arkansas’s progressive brackets. For example, a simplified
                structure might look like:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>First portion of income taxed at a low rate</li>
                <li>Next portion taxed at a higher rate</li>
                <li>Top portion taxed at the highest rate</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator applies each rate only to the income that falls
                within that bracket, not to your entire income.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Subtract Arkansas tax credits</h3>
              <p>
                Nonrefundable credits reduce your Arkansas tax liability but
                cannot reduce it below zero. Examples include certain dependent
                or low‑income credits. Enter the total amount of credits you
                expect to claim; the calculator subtracts them from your gross
                Arkansas tax.
              </p>

              <h2>Using the Arkansas income tax calculator effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose the correct filing status.</strong> Your
                  brackets and standard deduction depend on whether you file as
                  single, married filing jointly, married filing separately, or
                  head of household.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use realistic income estimates.</strong> For the best
                  results, use your year‑to‑date pay information or last year’s
                  return as a starting point.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Include Arkansas‑specific deductions and credits.</strong
                  >
                  If you know your Arkansas itemized deductions or credits,
                  enter them to refine the estimate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compare withholding.</strong> Add your Arkansas tax
                  withheld to see whether you are likely to receive a refund or
                  owe additional tax.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool focuses on
                  <strong>Arkansas state income tax only</strong>. It does not
                  calculate federal income tax, FICA, or local sales taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It uses a simplified model of Arkansas brackets and deductions
                  for planning purposes and may not match your final return
                  exactly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Special rules for capital gains, retirement income, part‑year
                  residents, and nonresidents are not fully modeled.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always refer to the Arkansas Department of Finance and
                  Administration (DFA) instructions or consult a tax
                  professional for filing decisions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Arkansas income tax</h2>

              <h3>Who has to file an Arkansas income tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                Generally, Arkansas residents must file if their gross income
                exceeds the filing threshold for their status, or if they had
                Arkansas tax withheld and want a refund. Nonresidents and
                part‑year residents must file if they earned income from
                Arkansas sources. Thresholds and rules change, so always check
                the latest DFA guidance.
              </p>

              <h3>Does Arkansas tax Social Security and retirement income?</h3>
              <p>
                Arkansas does <strong>not</strong> tax Social Security
                retirement benefits. Some other retirement income (such as
                pensions and IRA distributions) may be partially exempt up to
                certain limits. This calculator does not model each exemption
                separately, so if a large portion of your income is retirement
                income, your actual Arkansas tax may be lower than the estimate.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Are Arkansas income taxes high compared with other states?
              </h3>
              <p>
